  {
    "objectID": "chapters/aju_ranga_khelata.html#lyrics",
    "href": "chapters/aju_ranga_khelata.html#lyrics",
    "title": "Rāg Behāg",
    "section": "Lyrics",
    "text": "Lyrics\n\nSthāyī\n\nāju raṅga khelata hori baraja me dhuma maco ri\n\nAntarā\n\nśyāmasundara braja nāgara ke rasa dekhata guruyana corī\n\nSañcārī\n\ngāve bajāve rasa upajāve raṅga bhara kañcana kī picakārī\n\nĀbhog\n\ncuvā candana aura aragajā abīra liye barajorī\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nNoteReading the notation\n\n\n\n\n\nDhamār tāl is a 14-beat cycle divided as 5 + 2 + 3 + 4 (vibhāgs marked X, 2, O, 3). Each row below shows one complete cycle: the fourteen columns correspond to beats 1–14, with sam X at beat 1, 2 at beat 6, O (khālī) at beat 8, and 3 at beat 11.\nThe sargam row gives the notes; the bold text row below it gives the lyrics syllables. A dash - indicates a held note or empty beat. Brackets \\(\\lb{\\cdot}\\) denote meend (glide); superscripts \\(\\sps{\\cdot}\\) indicate the starting grace note of a glide; \\(\\tr{X}\\) denotes a note in the upper octave (tār saptak); \\(\\mn{X}\\) denotes a note in the lower octave (mandra saptak)."
  },
